***basic commands (pwd, cd, mkdir, ls, cp, mv, rm)

pwd
    print working directory, shows current location

cd 
    change directory

mkdir 
    make directory
    use -p and slashes between to create parent/nested directories

        mkdir -p genetics/lab 
            this will create one working directory "genetics" with a directory "lab" within it

ls 
    list files and directories
        -f shows types
        -l long format
        -a hidden files 
        -h human readable sizes
        -lrth shows file size

    
        blue- directory- you can cd to it
        white/grey- regular file - you can cat,less,head,tail it
        red- compressed file - must unzip first
        green- executable file

wc
    to list the number of files or lines
    
        wc -l lists the lines of text of a defined file

        ls code | wc -l
            lists the number of folders within code

cp 
    copy  command+source+destination

    cp -r 
        copies directories
    
    if you want to move a file to a directory
        cp filename directory/

    if you want to move a folder to a directory
        cp -r folder directory/

    if you want to copy a file to current directory under a new name
        cp oldfoldername newfoldername 

    move a file to new directory and name at same time
        cp olderfoldername directory/newfoldername 
    
mv 
    move and rename , removes old file destination
    make sure the current directory is destination

    just rename folders
         mv oldfoldername/ newfoldername/

    move two at once
         mv oldfile.txt oldfile2.txt folder/


    
rm
	Remove 
	
    remove files
		rm file.fastq

	remove directories
		rm  -r  old_results_folder/

	get prompted with a safety net,  -i
		rm  -i  *.fastq

	force -f
		forces the remove command without safety net



***more specific commands, (chmod, >, >>, grep, |, echo, cut)

chmod 
    change file permissions
        r read
        w write
        x execute

    first part is user (u)
    second part is group (g)
    third part is others (o)

    - is remove permissions
    + is add permissions

    chmod +x script.sh 
        adds execute permissions for everyone
    
    chmod g+r script.sh
        adds permissions for group to read
    
    chmod u-w script.sh
        removes permissions for the user to write

    how to see viewer permissions?
         ls -laF

grep
    searching within files, usually within fastq files

        must use "" for each phrase to find (or use $ before grep- less common)
        after "" ask for which file grep is searching within
            grep -letter # "phrase" file.fastq

        -B # will show # of lines before phrase
        -A # will show # of lines after phrase
        -C # will show # of lines before and after phrase
        -c will count how many reads of the phrase exists
        -v will show everything but the phrase
        -n tells which line the phrase is on
        -i shows each time the phrase occurs, capital or lowercase

        ^ (start of phrase) will find lines starting with phrase    
            grep "^@SRR" file.fastq
        
        $ (end of line) will find lines ending with phrase
            grep "TTT$" file.fastq

        "history | grep "" " lists the lines of "" that has been previously typed


>  redirection operator
    will dump before text to new file, deleting old text

    cat oldfile > newfile
    deletes oldfile
>>
    ammend
    adds moving data to the bottom of new file

    cat oldfile >> newfile 
        keeps oldfile 

|
    pipe takes the output of one command and sends it as the input of a second command
        how many sequences are in this file?
             cat SRR098026.fastq | wc -l

echo 
    prints text or variables to terminal
    can add text to file with >> or replace text within a file with >

    can show you what will occur in a command 
        echo mv oldfile newfile
            shows you what the change would be 

cut 
    will remove 
        -d is the deliminator with a given ''
        -f# is the fields at which there was a cut 

    for example, 
    ls *.txt | cut -d'.' -f1
            this lists all files with .txt but only the first field, what is the text before the first .

        this takes all files with .txt at the end and cuts it at the period
        then it will list the field 1, so the field before the period, field 2 would list txt


WHAT IS * ?

    this is the special wildcard

    if * is BEFORE something, it will tell give you all the files/directories that end with that
        ls /bin/*.txt    
                lists all the files with .txt at the end 
    
    if * is AFTER something, it will tell give you all the files that start with that
        ls /bin/file*
                lists all the "file" 
    
    if * is before and after, it will give you all of the things that contain what is between the *
        ls /bin/*a*
                lists all the things in bin containing a


***VIEWING A FAST Q

    cat views all
        should not use

    less views "less" content
        -S chops long lines instead of wrapping the text
        type in the specific phrase to search for it
        g jump to top
        G jump to bottom
        q quit

    head views top part
        -n #  shows the specific number of lines (line*4 because each fastq is 4 lines)
            head -n 4 SRR098026.fast q 
                shows the first line of fastq file

    tails views bottom part
         -n #  shows the specific number of lines (line*4 because each fastq is 4 lines)
            tail -n 8 SRR098026.fastq
                shows the last two lines of the fastq file

    zcat allows viewing of a compressed .gz fastq file
        pipe this command for specific viewing function
            zcat file.gz | head
    unzip allows for viewing of a compressed .zip fastq file
            unzip file.zip | head


    Fastq format:
        @ Title length=
        Sequences
        + and then the title again for space length=
        quality score

***LOOPS

    $ for 
    >do
    >
    >mv
    >done 

    for example
    
    $ for filename in *.txt
    >do> name=$(basename ${filename} .txt)
    >mv ${filename} ${name}_2019.txt
    > done

$ for starts the loop, 
    $ for filename in *.txt 
        looks for every file in this folder that ends in .txt and puts 
        in a temperary bucket called filename 

    >do>  action

    name=$ (down below)
        creates a variable

    (basename ${filename} .txt)

        whats in the perentheses before

        strips the extension, takes the current file (ex. sample_1.txt) and 
        removes the .txt (sample_1)

    >mv ${filename} ${name}_2019.txt

        renames -new name + _2019.txt
        for example sample_1_2019.txt

    >done finalizes changes and closes loop



